# Playwright on every fix — no second smoke for the same bug

Andrew should **never** have to hardware-smoke the same regression twice. If a bug was fixed, a Playwright test must exist that **fails on the pre-fix commit and passes on the fix** — in the **same branch**, not a follow-up.

## Hard gate

Any change that fixes user-observable **behavior**, **visual/layout**, **chrome interaction**, **sync/lifecycle copy**, or **multi-peer flows** MUST include a Playwright test in the same commit series.

- **Location:** `tests/integration/*.spec.ts` (preferred — tutor+student relay harness).
- **Tags:** add domain tag(s) from [`tests/test-tags.ts`](../../tests/test-tags.ts) on each new test — enables selective `npm run test:wb-affected` (see [`.cursor/rules/test-selection.mdc`](test-selection.mdc)).
- **Merge gate enrollment:** add the spec (or new tests) to the `wb-regression` project in `playwright.config.ts` when the fix touches whiteboard, sync, chrome, recording UI, or live session flows.
- **Visual baselines:** layout/chrome-only fixes may use `tests/visual/` when a screenshot oracle is the right guard.

## What counts as coverage

| Fix type | Playwright oracle (examples) |
|---|---|
| Sync / graph / strokes | Relay invariant, E2E bridge + `waitFor*` on peer state |
| Banner / pill copy | `toHaveText` / `not.toContainText` on `data-testid` |
| Chrome clickability | Click control → assert DOM/state change |
| Alignment / sizing | `boundingBox()` midline compare (tolerance ≤ few px) |
| Exit / rejoin / presence | Two-browser harness; assert pills, not waiting |

Use an **independent oracle** (library transform, peer count, graphStateJson) — not constants back-derived from the buggy implementation.

## Jest is not enough

`jest` / jsdom **do not** satisfy this rule for layout, coordinates, flyout clipping, real render cadence, or Excalidraw embed behavior. Jest may supplement; it does not replace Playwright for these surfaces.

## Narrow exceptions (rare — must be explicit)

Some failures only reproduce on **real external environments** with no hermetic stand-in (e.g. Teams desktop WebRTC, iOS Safari background suspension, device-only GPU quirks).

When Playwright truly cannot approximate the failure:

1. Add the **closest surrogate** test that catches the wiring/class of bug (split-brain banner when sync roster present ≠ Teams ICE).
2. If no surrogate is credible: `test.describe.skip` with a `// PLAYWRIGHT-GAP:` comment naming the gap + a **`docs/BACKLOG.md`** entry.
3. **Silent omission is forbidden** — orchestrator blocks merge without a named test OR a documented gap.

## Orchestrator + executor checklist

Before calling a fix wave done:

- [ ] Each bug in the fix list maps to **one Playwright test** (`file` → `test("…")` title).
- [ ] New specs are in `wb-regression` (or visual project) so `npm run test:wb-playwright` / `test:wb-sync` runs them.
- [ ] Handoff names the tests — Andrew's smokebook validates **new** surface area only, not re-proof of old regressions.

**Rule of thumb:** If Andrew already smoked it and it broke again, we failed this rule.
